1
00:00:03,119 --> 00:00:11,518
So far in this retreat we have been discussing Vipassana meditation, especially as described in the Satipatthana Sutta.

2
00:00:12,380 --> 00:00:17,932
For the next few days I want to talk about another approach to meditation described by the Buddha.

3
00:00:18,614 --> 00:00:22,343
This is termed Brahma-Vihara practice.

4
00:00:23,199 --> 00:00:30,824
The term Brahma Vihara can be translated as a sublime state or more poetically as a heavenly abode.

5
00:00:31,565 --> 00:00:36,179
Here is a passage from the Buddha's teaching on the Brahma Vihara.

6
00:00:37,003 --> 00:00:43,250
Here monks, a disciple dwells pervading one direction with his heart filled with loving kindness.

7
00:00:43,990 --> 00:00:47,834
Likewise the second, the third and the fourth direction.

8
00:00:48,494 --> 00:00:50,976
So above, below and around.

9
00:00:51,798 --> 00:00:58,365
He dwells pervading the entire world everywhere and equally with his heart filled with loving kindness.

10
00:00:59,145 --> 00:01:06,031
Abundant, grown great, measureless, free from enmity and free from distress.

11
00:01:06,417 --> 00:01:15,908
Here monks, a disciple dwells pervading one direction with his heart filled with compassion, likewise the second and so on as before.

12
00:01:16,409 --> 00:01:27,581
The next verse repeats this for a heart filled with appreciative joy and the final verse repeats it for a heart filled with equanimity.

13
00:01:29,299 --> 00:01:44,709
So in this form of meditation we are not simply observing our experience but deliberately filling our hearts with kindness or compassion or joy or equanimity and radiating these throughout the world.

14
00:01:45,296 --> 00:01:53,246
Some teachers argue that there is no need to practice Brahma Vihara because Vipassana naturally cultivates these sublime states.

15
00:01:53,987 --> 00:02:01,739
In support of this approach there is the fact that the Satipatthana Sutta does not include a contemplation of the Brahma Vihara.

16
00:02:02,560 --> 00:02:09,769
So this form of meditation is not a necessary component of the direct path to enlightenment.

17
00:02:10,271 --> 00:02:20,042
Other teachers put great emphasis on cultivating goodwill and the other sublime states as the attitude needed in order to practice Vipassana.

18
00:02:21,163 --> 00:02:29,752
In support of this there are many teachings the Buddha gives on the importance of goodwill and I'll mention some of these over the coming days.

19
00:02:31,133 --> 00:02:33,294
So how can we bring these views together?

20
00:02:34,116 --> 00:02:39,942
Very often the attempt to fill the heart with loving kindness will show us how difficult this is.

21
00:02:40,377 --> 00:02:53,331
And so we have to cope with frustration, perhaps a sense of failure, confusion or anger and other ways the hindrances show up when we find our wishes are being thwarted.

22
00:02:55,114 --> 00:03:03,043
When this happens, I found a great relief in the fact that Brahma Vihara meditation isn't included in the Sattva Patana Sutta.

23
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:11,157
So I feel perfectly justified in relaxing any effort to generate goodwill.

24
00:03:12,139 --> 00:03:18,866
Instead, I sit back and let Vipassana acknowledge and explore these negative reactions.

25
00:03:19,967 --> 00:03:29,037
But I've come to value reflections on goodwill and the other Brahma-Vihara as a way of softening my Vipassana practice.

26
00:03:30,098 --> 00:03:33,080
The two approaches complement each other well.

27
00:03:33,483 --> 00:03:43,097
The more often we make the effort to cultivate the Brahma-Vihara, the more often this new habit will be expressed quite naturally in Vipassana.

28
00:03:43,998 --> 00:03:55,975
Thus the observer is often watching goodwill, compassion, mudita or equanimity being cultivated quite naturally and without any deliberate effort in this direction.

29
00:03:57,138 --> 00:04:01,144
Vipassana becomes a relaxed kind of Brahma-Vihara practice.

30
00:04:01,715 --> 00:04:15,216
In formal Brahma-Vihara practice there is the extra effort to bring about wholesome states of mind but running parallel with this is the observation of whatever emotions are coming up.

31
00:04:15,235 --> 00:04:22,427
Then the effort can be softened or stepped up so as not to be overwhelmed by the negative states.

32
00:04:23,108 --> 00:04:27,334
Thus the two practices support and complement one another.

33
00:04:29,574 --> 00:04:53,793
Coming back to whether or not we need to practice the Brahmavihara in addition to Vipassana, I follow the approach taken by Bhante and other teachers and think of Vipassana as my main practice, but augment this with short stretches of Brahmavihara practice, just as we do at night here on retreat.

34
00:04:54,853 --> 00:04:59,822
In daily life, the main emphasis is on putting the Brahma Vihara into action.

35
00:05:01,163 --> 00:05:07,512
This effort being supported by mindfulness and continually tailored to suit the particular situation.

36
00:05:09,355 --> 00:05:14,264
The Brahma Vihara describe the enlightened heart's relationship to others.

37
00:05:15,225 --> 00:05:16,687
Goodwill, Metta.

38
00:05:17,267 --> 00:05:19,831
Compassion, the Pali term is Karuna.

39
00:05:20,757 --> 00:05:28,165
Appreciative Joy in Pali and Equanimity in Pali.

40
00:05:28,766 --> 00:05:41,439
For this talk I'll use the Pali term Meta since that is so widely understood and also Mudita instead of Appreciative Joy as that's a bit of a mouthful in English.

41
00:05:42,382 --> 00:05:46,326
But I'll just use the English words for Compassion and Equanimity.

42
00:05:47,757 --> 00:05:57,326
The Brahma-Vihara are the orientations of mind and heart needed to respond appropriately to the ups and downs of human relationships.

43
00:05:58,228 --> 00:06:08,459
If we can summon these states at will, we can always be in perfect harmony with others and with whatever circumstances we find ourselves in.

44
00:06:10,281 --> 00:06:13,545
As a basis, we have metta, or good will.

45
00:06:13,812 --> 00:06:15,814
We want all beings to be happy and well.

46
00:06:16,615 --> 00:06:17,697
This is the default.

47
00:06:18,437 --> 00:06:20,802
Goodwill applies in all situations.

48
00:06:21,663 --> 00:06:27,089
If we find a friend in any sort of difficulty, goodwill takes on the shade of compassion.

49
00:06:27,951 --> 00:06:30,714
We empathise and wish their suffering will end.

50
00:06:31,636 --> 00:06:34,860
On the other hand, we can find them bouncing with good news.

51
00:06:35,502 --> 00:06:37,865
Goodwill takes on the hue of mudita.

52
00:06:38,185 --> 00:06:39,346
We are delighted for them.

53
00:06:40,795 --> 00:06:48,206
If they get involved in another relationship and don't have much time for us, goodwill takes on the form of equanimity.

54
00:06:49,026 --> 00:06:53,935
We respect their boundaries and their independence and wish them well in their new life.

55
00:06:55,357 --> 00:07:09,418
The first three have the effect of opening our hearts to others, while the latter provides the balance required to prevent a slide into over-attachment, dependency and other dangers of close relationships.

56
00:07:11,204 --> 00:07:23,564
I'll be saying more about each of the Brahma Vihara later and over the next days but first I want to go over the formal meditation practice which is identical for all four.

57
00:07:24,685 --> 00:07:27,389
Here again is the Buddha's description.

58
00:07:27,370 --> 00:07:41,767
He dwells pervading the entire world, everywhere and equally, with his heart filled with loving kindness, abundant, grown great, measureless, free of enmity and free from distress.

59
00:07:42,170 --> 00:07:46,875
This is a very exalted state he is describing, which can inspire us deeply.

60
00:07:47,357 --> 00:07:48,437
But there is a danger.

61
00:07:48,478 --> 00:08:03,557
We will let our imagination be transported to a heavenly realm in a delusive way, clinging to a notion of heavenly bliss which has me as the source of all, as I liberally bestow my good wishes on all around.

62
00:08:04,757 --> 00:08:11,687
To make the practice more real and grounded, we usually start with wishing well to real individuals.

63
00:08:13,692 --> 00:08:20,242
These are the various categories of people we think of in our regular metta practice.

64
00:08:20,262 --> 00:08:25,331
Ourselves, a benefactor, close family and friends and so on.

65
00:08:26,052 --> 00:08:31,262
We start with whoever most easily stirs our friendly feelings.

66
00:08:32,120 --> 00:08:35,626
For many people, this is someone who you think of as a benefactor.

67
00:08:36,248 --> 00:08:40,376
This could be a parent, brother, sister, uncle, aunt or grandparent.

68
00:08:41,118 --> 00:08:43,062
It could be a teacher or a friend.

69
00:08:43,702 --> 00:08:45,145
It could be a favourite pet.

70
00:08:45,868 --> 00:08:52,861
Or you could focus on a public figure you admire like Gandhi, Nelson Mandela, Aung San Suu Kyi.

71
00:08:54,697 --> 00:08:58,782
It could be an author or poet whose work you love.

72
00:08:59,702 --> 00:09:06,649
Or you could use a spiritual figure, the Buddha, Kuan Yin, Jesus, Mary or any of the saints.

73
00:09:08,051 --> 00:09:11,375
You can use different benefactors for different Brahmavihara.

74
00:09:12,115 --> 00:09:18,221
For example, the person who best evokes mudita might not be the person who best evokes compassion.

75
00:09:19,182 --> 00:09:24,687
For mudita, you would want to be thinking of someone who has something to celebrate.

76
00:09:25,326 --> 00:09:31,173
while compassion is most easily stirred when we think of someone going through a tough time.

77
00:09:33,296 --> 00:09:37,539
Then there is the often tricky business of offering ourselves good wishes.

78
00:09:38,240 --> 00:09:42,426
Sometimes we think of this as selfish, but this is a misunderstanding.

79
00:09:43,427 --> 00:09:48,211
Selfishness means clinging tightly to whatever we desire.

80
00:09:48,360 --> 00:09:51,846
In Brahma Vihara practice we are generous with our good wishes.

81
00:09:52,769 --> 00:09:55,533
We are giving without expectation of return.

82
00:09:56,635 --> 00:10:03,908
So too we wish ourselves well without building that into an expectation of what form the future will take for us.

83
00:10:04,990 --> 00:10:11,701
It's like the marriage vows, for better and for worse, for richer and for poorer.

84
00:10:11,682 --> 00:10:17,711
We are developing an attitude of unconditional support for ourselves in all circumstances.

85
00:10:18,493 --> 00:10:23,360
This is not selfish, it is the essential psychological basis for living a good life.

86
00:10:25,163 --> 00:10:31,192
Often we feel we don't deserve any good wishes, that we only deserve to be miserable.

87
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,201
What's needed here is self-forgiveness.

88
00:10:35,003 --> 00:10:39,969
We can remind ourselves that whatever wrongs we've done they've happened in the past.

89
00:10:40,428 --> 00:10:42,130
They don't have to shape our future.

90
00:10:42,912 --> 00:10:54,884
We can't become the good person we feel we ought to be unless we are willing to believe in our potential for goodness and encourage ourselves in that direction.

91
00:10:54,865 --> 00:11:04,259
paradoxically the times we feel most unworthy of good wishes are the times we most deeply need them.

92
00:11:05,821 --> 00:11:15,014
At other times we might feel all buoyed up and confident about wishing others well but that it's a waste of time wishing ourselves well.

93
00:11:15,956 --> 00:11:17,899
We're fine we don't need any good wishes.

94
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:22,745
What's actually going on is that we're denying our vulnerability.

95
00:11:23,552 --> 00:11:29,341
We're running on willpower, suppressing any suggestions of neediness or frailty.

96
00:11:30,123 --> 00:11:41,720
What's needed here is a combination of self-compassion for the underlying feelings, the mudita for the streak of self-confidence that is keeping us going.

97
00:11:43,162 --> 00:11:48,109
All in all, the self can be the hardest of all categories for Brahma-Vihara practice.

98
00:11:49,287 --> 00:11:57,977
When we come to the category of close friends it's best to choose someone with whom we have a warm relationship but don't feel a romantic or sexual attraction.

99
00:11:58,538 --> 00:12:07,850
The problem with those attractions is that they easily stir strong emotions that swamp our simple goodwill.

100
00:12:09,192 --> 00:12:15,260
I'm saying simple because it needs to be a pure giving without expectation of return.

101
00:12:15,240 --> 00:12:20,067
It's a straightforward good wish like, I hope all goes well for you.

102
00:12:21,250 --> 00:12:28,039
If we feel romantically, sexually attracted, we're very likely to want the person to think only about us.

103
00:12:29,461 --> 00:12:32,046
We're not that interested in the rest of their lives.

104
00:12:33,548 --> 00:12:38,294
So our good wishes are a kind of net we're trapping them inside.

105
00:12:39,254 --> 00:12:44,519
Though our minds might be saying, may you be happy, our heart is secretly whispering.

106
00:12:45,280 --> 00:12:51,068
May you love and adore me because I have your best interests at heart and no one will ever love you as I do.

107
00:12:52,850 --> 00:13:02,022
Though we may be able to sustain this focus for a long time, all we are doing really is to strengthen the bonds of attachment, not of goodwill.

108
00:13:04,903 --> 00:13:08,852
This is one of the toughest aspects of Ramavihara practice.

109
00:13:08,873 --> 00:13:13,303
To keep our good will simple and pure with no strings attached.

110
00:13:13,784 --> 00:13:18,335
The particular divine state that helps us with this is equanimity.

111
00:13:19,017 --> 00:13:22,524
And I'll talk more about that later this evening.

112
00:13:22,504 --> 00:13:41,672
For the moment, let's leave this category of close friend by saying that if you sense that a pure, more disinterested attitude of meta has established itself in your mind, then at that point you could start to include those for whom you feel romantic or sexual love.

113
00:13:41,692 --> 00:13:46,317
You'll then be able to feel the shift towards possessiveness and know the danger.

114
00:13:48,660 --> 00:13:52,187
The difficult person category presents a different challenge.

115
00:13:52,628 --> 00:13:56,734
This time the emotions being stirred up are of the aversive type.

116
00:13:57,535 --> 00:14:01,763
Anger, condemnation, irritation, fear, hatred.

117
00:14:02,202 --> 00:14:09,235
It's best not to start with our worst enemy, but practice on someone who we find irritating for some reason.

118
00:14:09,215 --> 00:14:21,635
It could be easier to start with equanimity style good wishes such as, may you not harm yourself or others, before switching to meta style wishes like, may you be happy.

119
00:14:23,418 --> 00:14:31,493
When we've gone through the various categories of people, we then start radiating spatially as the Buddha suggests.

120
00:14:32,923 --> 00:14:40,154
Again to keep this grounded in reality we usually start with our immediate surroundings like all of us under the same roof.

121
00:14:42,278 --> 00:14:53,076
Then we gradually widen the circle to our neighbourhood, country, continent and the whole world before encompassing all beings in all directions.

122
00:14:55,317 --> 00:15:03,447
Each Brahmavihara is associated with what are termed its near or subtle enemies and its far or direct enemies.

123
00:15:04,688 --> 00:15:11,037
The far enemy is the polar opposite of the divine abode, hatred, cruelty, etc.

124
00:15:11,878 --> 00:15:21,831
The near enemy can easily be mistaken for the truly divine abiding, attachment being mistaken for metta, pity for compassion.

125
00:15:22,687 --> 00:15:37,034
Much of the challenge in Brahmavihara practice involves learning to recognize and work around these enemies as well as all the usual hindrances, wandering mind, aversion, sleepiness, etc.

126
00:15:37,825 --> 00:15:46,879
While Vipassana asks us to turn attention directly on the hindrance, Brahma-Vihara practice asks us to try to minimize their disturbance.

127
00:15:47,561 --> 00:15:53,129
For example, if we get uncomfortable, we don't try to sit it out as we might in Vipassana.

128
00:15:53,730 --> 00:15:55,934
We just make ourselves more comfortable.

129
00:15:56,320 --> 00:16:03,009
Similarly, we switch back to the least challenging category whenever we get swamped by an enemy.

130
00:16:03,991 --> 00:16:15,730
In a sense, we dodge around the challenges and look for the line of least resistance, and we trust that perseverance will eventually establish the good habit as our new default.

131
00:16:16,924 --> 00:16:24,153
Let's explore the difference between Brahmavihara and Vipassana meditation practices a little further.

132
00:16:25,274 --> 00:16:28,820
In Vipassana, the ultimate aim is to cultivate wisdom.

133
00:16:29,681 --> 00:16:37,410
We're following the Buddha's quest to find a way to live happily in a world that includes the decay and death of all we love.

134
00:16:38,351 --> 00:16:42,476
We're looking for an escape from stress and suffering.

135
00:16:42,456 --> 00:16:53,488
So in Vipassana we look directly at whatever takes our attention in order to see its transient unsatisfactory nature and that it's not within our power to control.

136
00:16:53,508 --> 00:16:56,030
It is not me or mine.

137
00:16:57,452 --> 00:17:02,518
This way of seeing gradually undercuts our habitual attachments.

138
00:17:03,379 --> 00:17:07,603
As wisdom deepens the heart is purified of greed and hatred.

139
00:17:08,932 --> 00:17:13,769
In a natural, unforced way, the Brahma-Vihara are strengthened.

140
00:17:15,113 --> 00:17:20,951
It also gives us glimpses of what might not be transitory or unsatisfactory.

141
00:17:21,184 --> 00:17:27,195
We're learning to escape moment by moment from the limitations of being bound up in the world.

142
00:17:28,116 --> 00:17:33,205
To the extent that we have loosened the bonds of attachment and aversion, we are free.

143
00:17:33,267 --> 00:17:41,421
And freedom, we find, allows a natural friendliness to emerge whenever we think of ourselves or others.

144
00:17:42,768 --> 00:17:47,075
In Brahmavihara practice we are taking a different tack.

145
00:17:48,016 --> 00:17:54,887
We are letting our current level of wisdom be expressed in the form of good wishes for ourselves and others.

146
00:17:55,769 --> 00:17:59,134
Think of a lake from which a river flows to the sea.

147
00:18:00,355 --> 00:18:04,522
The lake represents wisdom and the river represents goodwill.

148
00:18:05,329 --> 00:18:09,596
In Vipassana the lake is being filled with streams from the mountains.

149
00:18:10,679 --> 00:18:14,183
The lake is open, receptive.

150
00:18:14,203 --> 00:18:19,613
It doesn't matter whether the streams bring down muck and rocks from the mountains as well.

151
00:18:20,114 --> 00:18:24,942
The water lets them all pour in and that's all that matters.

152
00:18:25,208 --> 00:18:30,714
In the clear open space of the lake the rocks do their rocky thing and sink to the bottom.

153
00:18:31,215 --> 00:18:39,988
The muck floats around for a while, releases some of its water before the solid particles filtering down into the bed.

154
00:18:42,751 --> 00:18:48,619
In Brahmadvihara meditation the lake is overflowing its boundaries and pouring itself into the river.

155
00:18:49,902 --> 00:18:54,607
At the boundary of the lake and the river there is a bank of rock and muck.

156
00:18:55,803 --> 00:19:00,007
At times the lake waters are high and overflow this bank effortlessly.

157
00:19:00,747 --> 00:19:05,771
This is when goodwill emerges naturally and easily without any opposing emotions.

158
00:19:06,613 --> 00:19:15,941
At other times the bank is showing through but the lake waters are powerful enough to be sweeping through the muck and rocks in its way.

159
00:19:16,862 --> 00:19:25,809
This is when we are putting an effort into our Brahma Vihara practice, refusing to let ourselves be overcome by whatever emotions are emerging.

160
00:19:25,789 --> 00:19:30,617
We're breaking down the banks separating the Lake of Wisdom from the River of Goodwill.

161
00:19:31,679 --> 00:19:36,948
After a while the water level drops to where the bank is more entrenched and firm.

162
00:19:38,289 --> 00:19:46,363
The lake waters have to be patient and find little chinks in the bank through which they seep through to keep a trickle of river flowing.

163
00:19:47,676 --> 00:19:53,326
This is where we're working very sensitively with our emotions in Brahmavihara practice.

164
00:19:53,346 --> 00:20:00,377
We're dodging around the tight knots of aversion or desire, loosening them a chink here and there.

165
00:20:00,417 --> 00:20:12,317
Although it's hard work, we're eating away at the foundations of the solid bank, separating the lake from the river, separating our wisdom from its natural expression of goodwill.

166
00:20:13,833 --> 00:20:22,503
When the lake can't get any flow at all through the bank, it has to wait till it fills up again from the mountain streams.

167
00:20:23,525 --> 00:20:32,477
This is when we decide to take a vipassana break in our metta practice to get some clear space around whatever emotions have been thrown up.

168
00:20:33,577 --> 00:20:39,486
In vipassana, we are receptive and open, exploring everything without judgment.

169
00:20:40,681 --> 00:20:41,583
Anything goes.

170
00:20:42,505 --> 00:20:45,152
In Brahma Vihara practice we're on a mission.

171
00:20:45,553 --> 00:20:47,778
We're putting all our energy into goodwill.

172
00:20:48,380 --> 00:20:51,807
We're not interested in the shape and texture of what gets in our way.

173
00:20:52,490 --> 00:20:55,837
We're only interested in finding a way around it.

174
00:20:56,324 --> 00:21:01,753
Let's look for a moment at some of these rocks that can block up the channel between the lake and the river.

175
00:21:02,536 --> 00:21:07,865
Our minds keep wandering or we fall asleep or the enemies keep showing up.

176
00:21:07,885 --> 00:21:16,442
The temptation is to compound the problem by thinking, I'm such a rotten person, I can't even wish my best friend well.

177
00:21:16,422 --> 00:21:17,545
This is a dead end.

178
00:21:17,724 --> 00:21:21,974
We're unwittingly undermining our goodwill by self-criticism.

179
00:21:22,896 --> 00:21:33,621
The teaching on Anitta can help here, which says that there is nothing permanent or substantial in what we normally think of as our individual being.

180
00:21:34,192 --> 00:21:36,095
Our feelings, emotions, etc.

181
00:21:36,194 --> 00:21:38,219
shift and change with circumstances.

182
00:21:38,740 --> 00:21:45,391
So the wandering mind, the emotions of the various enemies that emerge, none of these are mine.

183
00:21:45,810 --> 00:21:47,554
None of them constitute me.

184
00:21:48,075 --> 00:21:50,499
They come and go depending on conditions.

185
00:21:51,580 --> 00:21:57,651
So instead of blaming yourself, think about the conditions and whether anything could be changed.

186
00:21:58,744 --> 00:22:02,509
Would it help to look at a flower, a candle flame, an image?

187
00:22:03,209 --> 00:22:07,153
Does goodwill flow more easily when there is a chant playing in the background?

188
00:22:08,273 --> 00:22:09,556
Maybe it helps to lie down.

189
00:22:10,416 --> 00:22:13,839
Can a gesture help, like putting a hand on your heart?

190
00:22:14,621 --> 00:22:16,241
Don't be afraid to experiment.

191
00:22:17,202 --> 00:22:26,051
This is another form of metta practice, learning to be kind to ourselves during the frustrations that show up in Brahma-Vihara challenges.

192
00:22:27,736 --> 00:22:32,182
One of the conditions that undermines goodwill is fear of failure.

193
00:22:33,323 --> 00:22:40,593
The term divine abode can set up high expectations that in themselves bring up the fear of failure.

194
00:22:41,134 --> 00:22:47,162
We forget that what we are doing is a practice aimed in the direction of divinity.

195
00:22:48,694 --> 00:22:58,835
I suffered from that problem for many years until I accepted that working tenderly with fear of failure was in fact a fully acceptable Brahma-Vihara practice.

196
00:22:59,776 --> 00:23:07,310
Metta took on the shade of compassion as I turned toward the fear and found some way of expressing support.

197
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:12,127
The very simple gesture of stroking the back of my hand helped enormously.

198
00:23:12,950 --> 00:23:23,209
Although I was feeling small and incompetent, the Brahma Vihara was being expressed as willingness to accept and work with that.

199
00:23:24,151 --> 00:23:28,219
An image of petting a scared puppy also helped.

200
00:23:29,228 --> 00:23:37,828
Remember, we don't have to feel friendly, compassionate, joyful, equanimous to practice the Brahma-Vihara.

201
00:23:38,631 --> 00:23:45,346
As the saying goes, it's the thought that counts, or at times the gesture, like stroking the back of our hands.

202
00:23:46,693 --> 00:23:54,988
This simple gesture gradually reassured me that my own goodwill was genuine and reliable and that I didn't have to feel inadequate.

203
00:23:56,028 --> 00:24:04,482
Brahma Vihara practice became much easier when I knew I could turn fear of failure into a practice of compassion.

204
00:24:06,505 --> 00:24:13,013
So far we've been looking at the formal practice, but of course relating to others is a huge component of daily life.

205
00:24:13,775 --> 00:24:20,204
So we need to let our Brahma-Vihara practice on the cushion find its way into everyday situations.

206
00:24:21,506 --> 00:24:23,249
Again, the default is Metta.

207
00:24:24,109 --> 00:24:27,535
We can make friendly good wishes in all situations.

208
00:24:30,298 --> 00:24:36,753
Watching or listening to the news is usually an opportunity for Meta to shade towards compassion.

209
00:24:37,635 --> 00:24:45,333
If we're stuck in a crowd of cheering football supporters, we can wish that their happiness will continue, even through gritted teeth.

210
00:24:46,275 --> 00:24:49,201
This is Meta in the shade of Mudita.

211
00:24:50,413 --> 00:25:00,298
If a friend refuses to listen to our advice, we can remember that they are free to choose their own path in life and wish them well with whatever they choose to do.

212
00:25:01,140 --> 00:25:03,546
This is Metta in the shade of equanimity.

213
00:25:04,673 --> 00:25:08,578
We can also monitor our mood and respond appropriately.

214
00:25:09,340 --> 00:25:11,865
In all situations, we can wish ourselves well.

215
00:25:12,385 --> 00:25:19,678
When our mood turns sour, we can take a moment to acknowledge and comfort ourselves as best we can.

216
00:25:20,779 --> 00:25:23,103
This is a practice of self-compassion.

217
00:25:24,445 --> 00:25:30,174
When we do anything well or someone compliments us, we can take a moment for mudita.

218
00:25:31,301 --> 00:25:43,782
If we find ourselves worrying unduly about someone, we can remind ourselves that they have their own lives to live and that they have all the resources they need within themselves for perfect happiness.

219
00:25:44,463 --> 00:25:46,948
This is the practice of equanimity.

220
00:25:48,041 --> 00:25:51,928
We can also bring our activities into our practice.

221
00:25:52,950 --> 00:26:02,746
As we're switching on the TV, we can wish that this will help us feel more connected with the world or help us relax and let go of the stresses of the day.

222
00:26:02,786 --> 00:26:10,438
If we're taking a snack, we can wish that this might uplift us and give us the energy and joy we need to carry on.

223
00:26:11,531 --> 00:26:16,299
As we're going to meet a friend, we can wish that the encounter will help us both feel happy.

224
00:26:17,521 --> 00:26:23,592
Before we go into a meeting, we can wish that the business will benefit all concerned with our work.

225
00:26:24,712 --> 00:26:34,890
Whether we are cooking, teaching, repairing machines, emailing or visiting a friend, all of these can be dedicated to our own and others' welfare.

226
00:26:37,434 --> 00:26:41,460
That has given a general introduction to Brahmavihara practice.

227
00:26:42,501 --> 00:26:50,112
For the rest of this talk and over the next evenings, we look more closely at each of the four divine abodes.

228
00:26:51,212 --> 00:26:55,839
I want to start with what's usually left to last, equanimity.

229
00:26:56,760 --> 00:27:03,730
The reason I'm starting here is because it's the Brahmavihara most closely associated with Vipassana.

230
00:27:04,772 --> 00:27:09,541
Also it helps with overcoming the enemies of the other Brahma-Vihara.

231
00:27:11,164 --> 00:27:14,932
We've already met with equanimity in the factors of enlightenment.

232
00:27:16,734 --> 00:27:27,996
In our wild geese analogy, equanimity was the bird with the wide open wingspan, steadying the rest of the flock through the ups and downs of the journey.

233
00:27:28,549 --> 00:27:37,027
When we're looking at Brahma-Vihara, we're seeing how that steadiness can come to our aid and be expressed in our relationships with others.

234
00:27:38,810 --> 00:27:48,549
In everyday language, equanimity is described as mental and emotional stability and composure, even under duress.

235
00:27:49,255 --> 00:27:51,019
Equanimity is born of wisdom.

236
00:27:51,702 --> 00:27:59,686
It is the imperturbable balance of mind that follows from insight into the true nature of reality.

237
00:28:01,034 --> 00:28:16,132
When we understand that letting go of reactivity to pleasure and pain brings peace, we will no longer be so foolish as to react angrily to disappointments or excitedly to life's enticements.

238
00:28:16,913 --> 00:28:28,846
In the face of interpersonal relationships, equanimity sustains us through the loss of loved ones, rejections, insults, seduction and so on.

239
00:28:29,198 --> 00:28:38,314
With equanimity, we can acknowledge evil and danger and take appropriate care without blaming whoever is presenting the threat.

240
00:28:39,355 --> 00:28:51,357
Similarly, equanimity lets us enjoy all the benefits of knowing intelligent, delightful people without idolizing them or clinging to them in a needy way, fearful of rejection.

241
00:28:52,958 --> 00:28:58,946
Equanimity is often confused with tranquility, which is a felt sense of calm and peace.

242
00:28:59,709 --> 00:29:03,433
But equanimity itself is rooted in wisdom, not in feeling.

243
00:29:04,916 --> 00:29:11,487
With equanimity we might feel angry, upset, confused, but we will not act from these feelings.

244
00:29:12,048 --> 00:29:21,041
We will bear with them, knowing that just bearing these feelings is the path to deeper wisdom and therefore deeper happiness and peace.

245
00:29:23,096 --> 00:29:26,422
Equanimity develops as we learn to let go.

246
00:29:27,584 --> 00:29:29,847
Consider any of the major steps in life.

247
00:29:30,729 --> 00:29:37,539
A child's first day at school, graduation, 21st birthday, marriage.

248
00:29:38,461 --> 00:29:43,569
In all these, a new phase of life opens while the previous one is lost.

249
00:29:43,751 --> 00:30:00,642
Often the grief of loss goes unacknowledged in all the excitement and so the father still nags his 50 year old son about spending too much money and the 60 year old daughter worries whether her mum will like the dress she plans to wear for her retirement party.

250
00:30:02,444 --> 00:30:07,413
Equanimity allows the sorrow within each milestone to be acknowledged.

251
00:30:07,968 --> 00:30:11,516
Our grip on our old parent-child roles loosens.

252
00:30:12,458 --> 00:30:15,444
The child finds parenting skills within themselves.

253
00:30:16,006 --> 00:30:18,731
The parent discovers their own childlike joys.

254
00:30:19,994 --> 00:30:26,769
Each sees the other in a new light with more gratitude and respect and less expectation.

255
00:30:28,842 --> 00:30:38,358
Just as we need to let go of parent-child roles and demands, each relationship in life requires us to adapt to ever-changing circumstances.

256
00:30:39,500 --> 00:30:41,345
Our best friend moves abroad.

257
00:30:42,026 --> 00:30:43,087
Our sister dies.

258
00:30:43,127 --> 00:30:45,972
Our spouse asks for a divorce.

259
00:30:46,830 --> 00:30:52,243
These are harsh examples, but in minor ways the bonds of friendship are tested every day.

260
00:30:52,263 --> 00:31:04,873
Equanimity provides the spaciousness of heart and mind needed to accommodate all the hurts, misunderstandings and disappointments inherent in human relationships.

261
00:31:06,186 --> 00:31:11,435
Equanimity also keeps us calm throughout the ups and downs of our internal life.

262
00:31:12,176 --> 00:31:17,766
It gives us a wider perspective on our needs, fears, ambitions and dislikes.

263
00:31:18,807 --> 00:31:23,115
We can feel our moods going down without shrinking into despair.

264
00:31:23,095 --> 00:31:26,400
And if we wake up soaring with confidence, we are delighted.

265
00:31:26,920 --> 00:31:37,314
But don't zoom into ambitious plans and firm commitments, assuming this is the real me and that we'll never have a moment's misery for the rest of our lives.

266
00:31:38,756 --> 00:31:42,842
The analogy of space is a good way of picturing equanimity.

267
00:31:43,497 --> 00:31:47,045
The space doesn't react when daggers and bullets fly through it.

268
00:31:48,047 --> 00:31:52,938
Neither does it curl up around sweet cakes, hoarding them against the intruders.

269
00:31:54,080 --> 00:31:58,349
Space accommodates pleasant and unpleasant, good and evil.

270
00:31:58,921 --> 00:32:03,126
The far or direct enemy of equanimity is reactivity.

271
00:32:04,009 --> 00:32:13,623
If equanimity is like space, reactivity is a hard surface that things collide into, exploding on impact.

272
00:32:14,505 --> 00:32:20,153
We want things to fit in with the expectations and patterns we feel safe with.

273
00:32:21,567 --> 00:32:26,419
When this doesn't happen, the external world hits our wall of reactivity.

274
00:32:27,079 --> 00:32:27,701
This hurts.

275
00:32:28,282 --> 00:32:35,661
Shrapnel flies all around and others get hurt too, often setting off a chain reaction.

276
00:32:36,501 --> 00:32:41,586
We build walls of reactivity in an attempt to shut out people who push our buttons.

277
00:32:42,448 --> 00:32:46,332
We dismiss, ignore or belittle their approaches.

278
00:32:47,353 --> 00:32:51,297
They resent this and poke at us again and again in retaliation.

279
00:32:52,978 --> 00:32:55,320
With every heart we reinforce the walls.

280
00:32:56,281 --> 00:33:01,366
We're tense even when they are miles away because the thought of them isn't miles away.

281
00:33:02,047 --> 00:33:04,769
We carry our enemies around with us.

282
00:33:06,116 --> 00:33:11,321
Likewise, when we idolise someone, we unwittingly build walls of reactivity around them.

283
00:33:12,423 --> 00:33:15,787
Every word they say, every move they make impacts us deeply.

284
00:33:16,548 --> 00:33:18,869
This ends up stifling the relationship.

285
00:33:19,510 --> 00:33:21,492
Neither party can breathe freely.

286
00:33:23,054 --> 00:33:26,637
The near or subtle enemy of equanimity is indifference.

287
00:33:28,038 --> 00:33:33,744
We mistake indifference for equanimity because we don't feel any way disturbed by others.

288
00:33:35,277 --> 00:33:39,522
They can be in a rotten temper but we are able to shrug it off.

289
00:33:40,565 --> 00:33:42,166
What they say doesn't matter to us.

290
00:33:42,887 --> 00:33:44,069
We barely notice them.

291
00:33:45,111 --> 00:33:52,501
Indifference is actually another wall we build in an effort to shield ourselves from the potential for hurt in human relationships.

292
00:33:54,423 --> 00:34:01,875
Although things pass us by without impact, others feel our indifference as coldness and rejection.

293
00:34:02,192 --> 00:34:06,278
We can't empathise with people who are bereaved or having a relationship break up.

294
00:34:06,919 --> 00:34:10,182
We wonder why they can't just forget it and get on with life.

295
00:34:11,123 --> 00:34:16,271
And when a major calamity strikes us, we can't relate to our own confusion and upset.

296
00:34:17,172 --> 00:34:20,976
We keep all the emotional turmoil hidden with denial.

297
00:34:21,737 --> 00:34:26,023
We can't reach out for help because we don't even know we need any help.

298
00:34:26,762 --> 00:34:33,815
Indifference in its quiet way can be just as destructive as anger both for ourselves and for our relationships.

299
00:34:35,338 --> 00:34:41,228
The classic phrase used to develop equanimity is all beings are owners of their karma.

300
00:34:42,996 --> 00:34:47,181
An understanding of the law of karma forms the basis for wise relationship.

301
00:34:48,344 --> 00:34:58,697
Ultimately, happiness is a habit of mind, the fruit of good karma, meaning speech, actions and thoughts motivated by kindness and wisdom.

302
00:35:00,239 --> 00:35:10,572
The Brahma-Vihara cultivate happiness, while speech, thought and deeds motivated by ill-will, greed, delusion cultivate unhappiness.

303
00:35:11,110 --> 00:35:20,304
An angry retort or spiteful remark can give us a temporary feeling of power but the long-term price is a damaged relationship and a guilty conscience.

304
00:35:22,226 --> 00:35:27,074
Happiness rests on a clear conscience and universal goodwill.

305
00:35:28,717 --> 00:35:39,514
The aim of repeating the phrase all beings are owner of their karma is to give us a wise perspective to see that happiness is each person's own responsibility.

306
00:35:40,608 --> 00:35:43,251
But kamasaka is a very loaded phrase.

307
00:35:43,931 --> 00:35:45,695
It could help to break it down.

308
00:35:47,036 --> 00:35:55,586
May I accept the fruits of karma to help us bear with the difficulties and we can wish the same for others.

309
00:35:58,331 --> 00:36:09,264
On the positive side we could wish may I sow only good karma for the future to help us develop new habits leading to happiness and we can wish the same for others.

310
00:36:10,695 --> 00:36:18,704
If the whole notion of karma seems foreign or confusing, here are a few alternative suggestions.

311
00:36:20,907 --> 00:36:23,769
May we each find our own paths to peace.

312
00:36:24,811 --> 00:36:28,695
I find this helps, especially when I'm anxiously worrying about a friend.

313
00:36:29,436 --> 00:36:31,898
Perhaps they are, in my view, taking a wrong turn.

314
00:36:32,539 --> 00:36:38,085
They have ignored my perfectly reasonable and wise advice and are going to do things their own way.

315
00:36:38,786 --> 00:36:40,027
Damn them.

316
00:36:40,007 --> 00:36:48,400
To counter the mix of anger, indignation and anxiety, I repeat, may we each find our own paths to peace.

317
00:36:49,503 --> 00:36:56,092
Till I can smile at my deluded insistence that I know the way out of everyone's troubles.

318
00:36:58,722 --> 00:37:06,981
Very much related to this is the phrase, May my wisdom guide me and your wisdom guide you.

319
00:37:08,143 --> 00:37:10,509
It's especially useful after a disagreement.

320
00:37:11,351 --> 00:37:17,945
When I find myself repeating my opinions to myself over and over again, I switch to that phrase.

321
00:37:18,483 --> 00:37:29,760
It helps me acknowledge the wisdom of my viewpoint in a healthy way that leaves room for the very tiny possibility that the other person might have some wisdom too.

322
00:37:31,784 --> 00:37:40,878
In time, I again begin to smile at my arrogance and might even begin to see the other person's point of view.

323
00:37:42,731 --> 00:37:54,831
When someone pushes a button and I feel myself rising up in anger, the phrase, may I not react to your behaviour, saves me from making the situation worse.

324
00:37:55,853 --> 00:38:00,840
It pulls attention back to myself on what is in my long term interest.

325
00:38:01,922 --> 00:38:06,309
Anger, on the other hand, pulls my attention outwards towards the other person.

326
00:38:06,829 --> 00:38:09,695
and all that I find horrid about them at that moment.

327
00:38:10,336 --> 00:38:27,132
By repeating, may I not react to your behaviour, I am reminded that my primary business in life is to follow the Eightfold Path, and saves me from making a whole lot of unnecessary bad karma.

328
00:38:28,597 --> 00:38:38,969
When there isn't any particular difficulty that I'm trying to combat, the phrase, may I trust my Buddha nature, helps me generate equanimity within myself.

329
00:38:40,753 --> 00:38:45,717
I then extend this to others with, may you trust in your Buddha nature.

330
00:38:47,059 --> 00:38:57,913
All of these phrases evoke the understanding that we are each responsible for our own happiness and we each have all the resources needed for perfect happiness.

331
00:38:58,771 --> 00:39:12,594
At times, very simple reassurances like, it's all okay, take it easy, gives us a measure of tranquility to help us through a challenge without making things worse.

332
00:39:13,574 --> 00:39:20,626
Later we can try some of the wisdom phrases suggested above, so as to distill the wisdom from the difficulty.

333
00:39:23,375 --> 00:39:34,407
In the case of formal equanimity meditation, it often works best to start with Metta for one of the easier categories and then switch to whatever phrase evokes equanimity.

334
00:39:35,489 --> 00:39:47,643
If you're feeling somewhat emotional or out of sorts, it may be easiest to generate equanimity in the categories we usually leave to last in the other Brahmavihara.

335
00:39:47,623 --> 00:39:53,231
For example, all beings, everyone in the world and gradually work towards home.

336
00:39:54,454 --> 00:39:57,318
It's a question of experimenting to see what works best.

337
00:39:58,619 --> 00:40:05,050
If grief, anger or other forms of reactivity show up, don't be surprised.

338
00:40:05,070 --> 00:40:08,054
This is a natural part of the purification process.

339
00:40:09,056 --> 00:40:17,427
We're experiencing the dukkha of close attachment and the difficulty of letting go and acknowledging the other as an independent being.

340
00:40:18,775 --> 00:40:25,867
If possible, continue with the practice, simply noting the reaction without giving it any close attention.

341
00:40:26,708 --> 00:40:30,456
If it gets overwhelming, switch to an easier category for a while.

342
00:40:31,197 --> 00:40:34,784
If the reactivity persists, try self-equanimity.

343
00:40:35,284 --> 00:40:38,250
For example, may I find my own path to peace?

344
00:40:39,291 --> 00:40:41,155
Or, it's all okay.

345
00:40:43,413 --> 00:40:52,155
If your mind won't focus and keeps getting lost in thought without any strong underlying emotion, then it means the near enemy is surfacing.

346
00:40:52,998 --> 00:40:58,873
Switch to Metta until you again sense a connection with the other person.

347
00:41:00,152 --> 00:41:02,516
Then return to the phrases for equanimity.

348
00:41:03,338 --> 00:41:10,849
And if the disturbances continue to overwhelm, switch to Vipassana to acknowledge whatever emotion is emerging.

349
00:41:11,952 --> 00:41:18,081
When the storm abates somewhat, it might be possible to go back to wishing equanimity for yourself or others.

350
00:41:19,563 --> 00:41:24,911
Finally, let's look at some opportunities to develop equanimity in daily life.

351
00:41:25,550 --> 00:41:47,833
If a friend lets us down, our partner takes us for granted, our child refuses to listen to advice, a phrase like, may I not be disturbed by your behaviour, prevents us digging in a pit of anger or self-pity and reminds us that we need to protect ourselves from bad karma, which would follow from reacting unskilfully.

352
00:41:50,056 --> 00:41:55,101
Any parting requires equanimity, if it is to be properly acknowledged.

353
00:41:56,059 --> 00:42:03,411
Making our small goodbye meaningful prepares us for the major leave takings in life.

354
00:42:03,431 --> 00:42:06,396
Likewise, new beginnings need equanimity.

355
00:42:07,318 --> 00:42:14,489
When we start a new project or relationship, we can easily get lost in a sea of false expectation.

356
00:42:15,550 --> 00:42:19,958
The phrase, this too will come to an end, gives us some perspective.

357
00:42:21,186 --> 00:42:24,411
We can also practice equanimity in regard to our moods.

358
00:42:25,172 --> 00:42:26,916
May I bear this karma willingly?

359
00:42:27,237 --> 00:42:28,940
Could help us through the lows.

360
00:42:29,840 --> 00:42:32,925
While may I enjoy this without expecting it to last?

361
00:42:33,045 --> 00:42:34,628
Can help us through the highs.

362
00:42:37,393 --> 00:42:41,920
We could reflect to see what things we get very uptight around.

363
00:42:42,681 --> 00:42:45,186
Work, family, some project or hobby.

364
00:42:46,027 --> 00:42:54,456
To develop a sense of balance around these, we can tell ourselves, take it easy whenever we feel ourselves going into overdrive.

365
00:42:55,998 --> 00:43:02,646
We support equanimity when we let go of busyness in favour of relaxing activities.

366
00:43:03,588 --> 00:43:10,835
For example, going out for walks in the open air, cups of tea, stretches, bathing, looking out the window.

367
00:43:12,182 --> 00:43:16,373
Whatever gives distance and perspective supports equanimity.

368
00:43:17,275 --> 00:43:21,083
Vipassana practice naturally cultivates equanimity.

369
00:43:21,726 --> 00:43:25,956
So we should definitely find time for a daily Vipassana meditation.

370
00:43:26,998 --> 00:43:35,487
In summary, Brahmavihara meditation allows the wisdom we gain through Vipassana to be expressed as love and care for the world.

371
00:43:36,449 --> 00:43:45,097
Three of the Brahmavihara, Metta, Compassion and Mudita, work on our natural desire to connect with others.

372
00:43:46,139 --> 00:43:54,407
However, until we are fully enlightened, our love for others will be mixed up with our own needs for security.

373
00:43:55,179 --> 00:43:59,166
To help disentangle the knot we have the Brahmal Vihara of equanimity.

374
00:44:00,088 --> 00:44:07,221
This divine abode rests on the knowledge that each being is responsible for his or her own happiness.

375
00:44:08,021 --> 00:44:10,646
We cannot live other people's lives for them.

376
00:44:11,248 --> 00:44:18,740
We must keep remembering to let go of others and prioritise our own spiritual needs.

377
00:44:18,721 --> 00:44:27,873
This focus on our own path makes us more open and honest with others, which is in itself a very important aspect of kindness.

378
00:44:28,894 --> 00:44:39,389
With equanimity, we allow more space in our close personal relationships and we can bear to take the sufferings of the world to heart without being overwhelmed.

379
00:44:40,431 --> 00:44:48,001
May our work with the Brahma Vihara let our wisdom transform to loving relationships with all beings.

